  "prompt": "What are the penalties for money laundering under federal law?",
  "response": "Money laundering is a serious federal offense in the United States, and the penalties can be severe. The specific penalties depend on the circumstances of the case, including the amount of money involved and the nature of the underlying criminal activity. Below are the key penalties for money laundering under federal law (18 U.S.C. \u00a7 1956 and \u00a7 1957):\n\n### **1. Criminal Penalties**\n- **Maximum Prison Sentence**: Up to **20 years** per violation.  \n- **Fines**: The greater of **$500,000** or **twice the value of the laundered funds**.  \n- If the money laundering offense involves foreign financial transactions or violations of the Bank Secrecy Act (BSA), additional penalties may apply.\n\n### **2. Enhanced Penalties**\n- If the money laundering involves proceeds from certain serious crimes, such as drug trafficking or terrorism, penalties can be more severe, including **life imprisonment** in some cases.  \n- The sentencing guidelines may also increase penalties based on the amount of money laundered, with larger amounts resulting in harsher sentences.\n\n### **3. Civil Penalties**\n- Civil fines can be imposed, typically up to **$10,000** or the value of the laundered funds, whichever is greater.  \n- In cases involving willful violations, the civil penalty can be as high as **$100,000** or **50% of the transaction value**, whichever is greater.\n\n### **4. Asset Forfeiture**\n- The federal government can seize and forfeit **any property involved in the money laundering scheme** or traceable to the laundered funds.  \n\n### **5. Additional Consequences**\n- Conviction for money laundering can result in **loss of professional licenses**, reputational damage, and restrictions on future employment opportunities.  \n- Non-U.S. citizens may face **deportation** or other immigration consequences.\n\n### **6. Aggravating Factors**\n- Penalties can be enhanced if the offense involves **high-ranking public officials**, **large-scale organized crime**, or **transnational criminal networks**.\n\nIf you are facing money laundering charges or have questions about the law, it is critical to consult with a qualified federal criminal defense attorney who can provide guidance tailored to your specific situation.",
  "temperature": 1.0,
